            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/time-tracking"]""",
            Tags = """["time-tracking","timers"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Time Tracking Overview\n\nTime Tracking records how you spend your working hours — which jobs you worked, for how long, and doing what kind of work. That time turns into the labor cost on each job and into the hours on your paycheck, so getting it right matters to you and to the shop.\n\n### Two Ways to Record Time\n\n**Live timer:** Click Start Timer when you begin a task, and Stop Timer when you finish. The page counts the minutes for you. Use this when you're working the task right now — it's the most accurate because you're not guessing.\n\n**Manual entry:** Click Manual Entry to write down time you already worked. Enter the date, hours, minutes, a category, and a note. Use this when you forgot to start a timer, or you're logging yesterday's work. Manual entries show a pencil icon so everyone can tell them apart from timed ones.\n\n### Categories\n\nTag each entry with the kind of work you did. This lets the office see where the hours go — how much is real production versus setup, inspection, or meetings.\n- **Production** — direct work making the part on a job\n- **Setup** — machine setup, tooling changes, fixture prep\n- **Inspection** — quality checks, measurements, first-article checks\n- **Maintenance** — equipment upkeep, cleaning, calibration\n- **Training** — learning a new job or skill, onboarding\n- **Meeting** — team meetings, planning, shift huddles\n- **Admin** — paperwork, emails, office tasks\n- **Cleanup** — end-of-shift cleanup, organizing\n- **Other** — anything that doesn't fit above\n\nCategories are optional, but picking one makes reports far more useful. Leave it blank only when nothing fits.\n\n### Clocking In and Out vs. Job Time\n\nClocking in and out is separate from job time. You clock in when you arrive and clock out when you leave — usually at the shop-floor kiosk, by scanning your badge and entering your PIN. That says when you were on-site. Job time entries say what you worked on while you were here. The office needs both: one shows you were present, the other shows what the shop got for that presence.\n\n### Linking Time to a Job\n\nMost of your time should be tied to a job so its cost lands where it belongs. The easy way: start the timer from the job's card on the shop-floor board — it links the job for you, no typing. Once linked, that job's number shows on the entry and the labor cost rolls into that job's total.\n\n### Finding Your Entries by Date\n\nUse the From and To date pickers to narrow the list — one day, a week, or a whole pay period. A summary line tells you the total hours and how many entries match. With no dates set, you see your recent entries.\n\n### When an Entry Locks\n\nAn entry stays editable while it's fresh. Once a manager locks it, or the pay period it falls in closes, it shows a lock icon and can no longer be changed or deleted on this page. You can still delete an unlocked entry from today or a future date; a past entry that's wrong has to go through a time correction (below).\n\n### Fixing a Past Entry\n\nGot the wrong duration or job on an entry from last week? A manager or admin fixes it under Admin > Time Corrections. They enter what it should say and a reason for the change. The original is kept on record, so there's always a clear trail of what changed and why. This is why you can't quietly edit old time — the correction keeps everyone honest.\n\n### Pay Periods and Overtime\n\nYour entries roll up into a pay period — weekly, every two weeks, twice a month, or monthly, whichever your shop uses. When the office closes a period, its entries freeze so the paycheck math stays put. If your shop pays overtime (say, over 40 hours in a week at time-and-a-half), the system splits your regular and overtime hours for you.\n\n### The Button Changes\n\nThe button at the top of the page is Start Timer when nothing is running, and switches to Stop Timer (showing the time so far) once a timer is going. So one glance tells you whether you're currently on the clock for a task.\n\n### Where the Hours Go\n\nEvery entry's hours times your pay rate becomes the labor cost on the job — that's how the shop knows what each job really cost to build. Those same hours feed your paycheck. Accurate time in, accurate costs and pay out.","sections":[]}"""
