            Tags = """["time-tracking","timers","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"tt1","text":"You need to track time for a 2-hour machine setup that happened yesterday. What is the correct approach?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Start a timer now and stop it after 2 hours"},{"id":"b","text":"Click Manual Entry, set the date to yesterday, enter 2 hours and 0 minutes, and select the Setup category","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Ask your manager to add it via the Admin panel"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a clock event with type 'setup' and a 2-hour duration"}],"explanation":"Manual entries are for logging time after the fact. Set the date to when the work was done, enter the duration in hours and minutes, and optionally select a category. Timer entries are for real-time tracking only."},{"id":"tt2","text":"You started a timer 45 minutes ago and need to stop it. Where do you find the stop button?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"In the same location as the Start Timer button — it changes to Stop Timer when a timer is running","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Right-click the active timer row in the table and select Stop"},{"id":"c","text":"Open the manual entry dialog and click Stop Active Timer"},{"id":"d","text":"Navigate to Admin > Time Tracking > Active Timers"}],"explanation":"The same button at the top of the page reads Start Timer when nothing is running and turns into Stop Timer (showing the time so far) once a timer is going. Click it to stop and save your entry — no need to hunt for the timer in the list."},{"id":"tt3","text":"What is the difference between a time entry and a clock event?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same thing — clock events are just time entries from the shop floor"},{"id":"b","text":"Time entries record what work was done and for how long; clock events record when an employee arrived at or left the facility","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Clock events track machine uptime; time entries track human labor"},{"id":"d","text":"Time entries are for salaried employees; clock events are for hourly workers"}],"explanation":"Time entries track work duration and can be linked to jobs and categories. Clock events track facility presence — when someone clocked in, clocked out, or took breaks. They serve different purposes but complement each other."},{"id":"tt4","text":"A time entry in the table shows a lock icon instead of a delete button. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The entry is linked to a job and cannot be modified without unlinking it first"},{"id":"b","text":"The entry is either locked by a manager/pay period or is a past-date entry that requires an admin correction to change","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The entry has already been paid out and can never be viewed again"},{"id":"d","text":"The entry belongs to another user and you don't have permission to delete it"}],"explanation":"The lock icon appears when an entry is locked (by a manager or pay period closure) or when it's a past-date entry. Only today's or future unlocked entries can be deleted directly. Past entries require an admin time correction so the change leaves a trail."},{"id":"tt5","text":"You want to see only the time entries from the first week of March. How do you filter the table?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Type '03/01' into the search box in the page header"},{"id":"b","text":"Set the From date to 03/01 and the To date to 03/07 using the date pickers in the filter bar","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Click the Date column header and select the date range from the dropdown"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Reports > Time Report and set the date range there"}],"explanation":"The filter bar has From and To date pickers. Set From to the start date and To to the end date. The table and summary line update automatically to show only entries within that range."},{"id":"tt6","text":"An active timer entry shows 'Running' in green in the Duration column. What happens if you close the browser and reopen the time tracking page?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The timer is lost — you need to manually add the time"},{"id":"b","text":"The timer is still running — it keeps counting from when you clicked Start, no matter what happens to your screen","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The timer pauses and you can resume it from where you left off"},{"id":"d","text":"The timer stops automatically and a manual entry is created for the elapsed time"}],"explanation":"A running timer isn't tied to your screen. It keeps counting from the moment you clicked Start, so closing the browser, losing power, or walking away doesn't stop it. Reopen the page and you'll see it still going with the right elapsed time. Just remember to stop it when you finish the task."},{"id":"tt7","text":"You started a timer on your laptop. Will it show as running on your phone's browser too?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"No — timers are per-device and per-session"},{"id":"b","text":"Yes — your running timer shows up on every device you're signed in on","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only if you manually refresh the page on your phone"},{"id":"d","text":"Only if both devices are on the same network"}],"explanation":"Your running timer follows you, not the screen you started it on. Open the page on your phone and you'll see the same timer going, with the top button reading Stop Timer. That's a safeguard — it stops you from starting a second timer and double-counting your hours."},{"id":"tt8","text":"A manager needs to correct a time entry from last week that has the wrong duration. What is the proper process?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the entry and create a new one with the correct duration"},{"id":"b","text":"Use Admin > Time Corrections, select the entry, change the duration, and provide a reason for the correction","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Edit the entry directly in the data table by double-clicking the duration cell"},{"id":"d","text":"Ask the employee to submit a new manual entry with the correct hours"}],"explanation":"Admin time corrections preserve an audit trail. The manager enters the corrected values and a required reason. The original values are kept in the audit trail so there is a complete record of what changed and why."},{"id":"tt9","text":"What categories are available when starting a timer or creating a manual entry?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only Production and Setup — other categories must be created in Admin settings"},{"id":"b","text":"None, Production, Setup, Inspection, Maintenance, Training, Meeting, Admin, Cleanup, and Other","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Categories are not available for timers, only for manual entries"},{"id":"d","text":"The category list is custom per company — there are no default categories"}],"explanation":"You get the same category choices whether you're starting a timer or logging a manual entry: None (the default), Production, Setup, Inspection, Maintenance, Training, Meeting, Admin, Cleanup, and Other. Picking one is optional, but it makes reports much more useful."},{"id":"tt10","text":"How is a time entry linked to a job for cost tracking?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You must manually type the job number into the notes field"},{"id":"b","text":"A time entry can be tied to a job — when you start a timer from a job's card on the shop-floor board, the link is set for you","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Jobs are linked after the fact by running a batch report in Admin"},{"id":"d","text":"All time entries are automatically linked to whatever job you happen to be looking at"}],"explanation":"A time entry can be tied to a job, and the easiest way is to start the timer right from that job's card on the shop-floor board — the link is set for you, no typing. The linked job number then shows in the Job column, and your labor cost lands on that job."},{"id":"tt11","text":"The summary line below the date filters shows '8.5 hours across 12 entries'. You change the From date to yesterday. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the summary only updates when you click a Refresh button"},{"id":"b","text":"The list narrows to the new date range and the summary line updates to match — new total hours and entry count","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The summary line stays the same but the table filters to show only yesterday's entries"},{"id":"d","text":"A confirmation dialog asks whether to apply the new filter"}],"explanation":"Changing a date picker narrows the list right away — no button to press. The summary line above the list recounts to match, so the total hours and entry count always describe exactly what you're looking at."},{"id":"tt12","text":"What does the 'Type' column badge tell you about a time entry?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the entry is billable (blue) or non-billable (gray)"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the entry was created via a live timer ('Timer' badge, teal) or logged after the fact ('Manual' badge, gray)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The entry's priority level — high (blue) or normal (gray)"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the entry has been approved by a manager (blue) or is pending (gray)"}],"explanation":"The Type label tells you how the time was captured. A teal 'Timer' means it was tracked live with Start and Stop, so it has exact start and end times. A gray 'Manual' means someone typed it in after the work was done. It's a quick way to see which entries were timed and which were entered from memory."}]}"""
