            AppRoutes = """["/time-tracking"]""",
            Tags = """["time-tracking","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Fixing a Past Entry\n\nYou can't just edit or delete an old time entry from the main list — a past or locked entry shows a lock icon instead of a delete button. That's on purpose: once time has been reviewed or paid, quietly changing it would throw off the job's cost and someone's paycheck. Instead, a manager or admin fixes it through a correction, which keeps a record of the change.\n\n- **Who does it:** managers and admins, under Admin > Time Corrections. A worker who spots a wrong entry flags it to their supervisor; they can't correct it themselves.\n- **What you can fix:** the date, how long it ran, the start and end times, the category, the notes, or which job it's tied to. Change only what's wrong and leave the rest.\n- **A reason is required.** You have to say why you're changing it — 'clocked onto the wrong job', 'forgot to stop the timer at lunch', and so on. That reason is saved with the change.\n- **The original is kept.** The correction records what the entry said before and what it says now, who changed it, and why. Nothing is erased.\n- **Why not just delete and re-add?** Deleting throws away the original record and the trail with it. A correction is the honest way to fix a past entry, so the shop's cost and pay totals still add up and anyone can see what happened.\n\n## Pay Periods, Locking, and Overtime\n\nYour entries add up into a pay period — the stretch of days one paycheck covers.\n\n- **How long a period is:** your shop picks weekly, every two weeks, twice a month, or monthly. An admin sets this once; it's the same for everyone.\n- **What's left in the period:** the page can show which period you're in and how many days are left before it closes — handy for knowing when to get your time squared away.\n- **Closing (locking) a period:** at the end, the office closes the period. Every entry in it locks — it shows a lock icon and can't be edited or deleted anymore, only fixed by a correction. Lock only after everyone's time is reviewed, because reopening is a hassle.\n- **Overtime:** if your shop pays overtime, the rule says when it kicks in — for example, over 8 hours in a day or over 40 in a week, paid at time-and-a-half, and sometimes double-time past a higher mark. The system splits your regular, overtime, and double-time hours for you; nobody tallies it by hand.\n- **The overtime breakdown:** a manager can pull up any worker's week and see regular vs. overtime vs. double-time hours, day by day. Use it to catch a bad clock-in before payroll, or to explain a paycheck to a worker who asks.\n\n## Clocking In at the Kiosk or on Your Phone\n\nClocking in and out is how the shop knows you were here. It's separate from job time — one says you're on-site, the other says what you worked on.\n\n- **At the kiosk:** step up to the shop-floor clock, scan your badge (or barcode), and enter your PIN. The screen shows whether you're currently clocked in, so you can tell at a glance if you already punched in.\n- **On your phone:** if your shop allows it, you can clock in and out from the mobile clock — useful for remote work, a job site, or when the kiosk line is long.\n- **What gets recorded:** each punch notes whether it's a clock-in, clock-out, break-start, or break-end; the time it happened; how you identified yourself (badge, barcode, or by hand); which kiosk or device you used; and an optional reason ('left early — doctor appointment').\n- **Breaks:** clock out for break and back in when you return, so unpaid break time isn't counted as worked hours.\n- **Presence vs. work:** clocking in proves you were here; your job time entries prove what you did while here. The office looks at both — hours on-site should line up with hours logged to jobs.\n\n## Where Your Hours Go — Job Cost and Pay\n\nEvery entry does double duty: it costs a job and it pays you.\n\n- **Onto the job:** when an entry is tied to a job (which happens for you when you start the timer from the job's card), your hours times your pay rate become that job's labor cost. A share of shop overhead is added on top, so the job carries its fair share of the building, power, and equipment. This is how the shop learns what a job really cost to build — and whether it made money.\n- **Down to the operation:** on jobs where you track time step by step, an entry can name the exact operation and the kind of time — setup, run (the usual), teardown, inspection, rework, wait, or other. That tells the planner where the hours actually went, so the next quote for that part is closer to reality.\n- **Onto your paycheck:** the hours in a pay period feed payroll, with regular and overtime split by your shop's rule. Accurate time in means an accurate check out — a missed clock-out or a wrong job hurts both the job's numbers and your pay.\n- **Into accounting:** if your shop keeps its books in a separate accounting system, the office passes approved hours across so labor lands in the financials. Once an entry has gone across, any further change belongs in accounting, not here — which is another reason old entries lock down.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Time Tracking training modules");
